05505nam a22009135i 9780520922365DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209223657 a10.1525/97805209223652doi  a(DE-B1597)543862  a(OCoLC)1153452506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE183.8.P19.C48 1999eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a327.73056941 aChristison, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerceptions of Palestine :bTheir Influence on U.S. Middle East Policy /cKathleen Christison.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (399 p.) :b1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Palestinians in the Nineteenth-Century Mind -- t2. Woodrow Wilson "Rising Above" Self-Determination -- t3. Franklin Roosevelt Locked In -- t4. Harry Truman History Belongs to the Victors -- t5. Eisenhower, Kennedy, Johnson Possession Is Nine-Tenths of the Law -- t6. Richard Nixon and Gerald Ford An Unrecognizable Episode -- t7. Jimmy Carter Making a Difference -- t8. Ronald Reagan Missed. Opportunities -- t9. George Bush No Illusions -- t10. The Pictures in Our Heads -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor most of the twentieth century, considered opinion in the United States regarding Palestine has favored the inherent right of Jews to exist in the Holy Land. That Palestinians, as a native population, could claim the same right has been largely ignored. Kathleen Christison's controversial new book shows how the endurance of such assumptions, along with America's singular focus on Israel and general ignorance of the Palestinian point of view, has impeded a resolution to the Arab-Israeli conflict.Christison begins with the derogatory images of Arabs purveyed by Western travelers to the Middle East in the nineteenth century, including Mark Twain, who wrote that Palestine's inhabitants were "abject beggars by nature, instinct, and education." She demonstrates other elements that have influenced U.S. policymakers: American religious attitudes toward the Holy Land that legitimize the Jewish presence; sympathy for Jews derived from the Holocaust; a sense of cultural identity wherein Israelis are "like us" and Arabs distant aliens. She makes a forceful case that decades of negative portrayals of Palestinians have distorted U.S. policy, making it virtually impossible to promote resolutions based on equality and reciprocity between Palestinians and Israelis.Christison also challenges prevalent media images and emphasizes the importance of terminology: Two examples are the designation of who is a "terrorist" and the imposition of place names (which can pass judgment on ownership).Christison's thoughtful book raises a final disturbing question: If a broader frame of reference on the Palestinian-Israeli conflict had been employed, allowing a less warped public discourse, might not years of warfare have been avoided and steps toward peace achieved much earlier?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aarab israeli conflict.  abiased reporting.  acultural identity.  aderogatory images.  agood faith relations.  aholocaust.  aholy land.  ahuman rights.  ainternational relations.  aisrael.  ajewish state.  amedia distortion.  amiddle eastern history.  amiddle eastern politics.  anative population.  apalestine.  apalestinians.  apeace negotiations.  apeace process.  aplace names.  arace relations.  aracism.  areligion.  areligious attitudes.  areligious